On the occasion of the most anticipated meeting in recent years, policy-makers in the Federal Reserve will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduras mahogany table to decide whether it’s time to raise a key rate of interest for the first interest rate.
Above them, at the end of the sitting room of the central bank, will be seen a mural of the United States.
The map is intended to remind that Janet L. Yellen, the President of the Fed, and his colleagues must put the nation’s economic interests above all else.
The Central Bank has received a double task from Congress: to maximize the employment rate in the United States and maintain price stability.
But since the big economic crisis, the Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be factor X in a too difficult to anticipate decision, which will be announced on Tuesday, and which will determine whether the U.S. economy is ready to be detached from the unprecedented incentive offered by the near-zero short-term interest rate of 2008 in force.
Although most data indicates a strong growth economy, the recent turmoil in global financial markets could frighten already cautious Fed officials from adding volatility by increasing the reference rate to federal funds – even by only a quarter percentage point.
“Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the first and main aspects that they will pursue,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the growing uncertainty in the global market is enough to give them arguments to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus on the decision the Fed will make, which in itself causes instability in the financial market.
Approximately half of Bloomberg’s recently surveyed economists anticipated an interest rate increase this week.
But financial markets are expected to delay the Fed, a key indicator showing that the probability of growth is only 30%.
This would indicate a downturn on the stock market if the Fed raises the interest rate, unless policymakers would mitigate the strike by promising that it would take a long time until the next rise.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16.599.85.
The move was triggered by expectations that the Fed’s decision-makers will keep interest rates stable this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
“It would be surprising if the Fed raise interest rates at this point,” Lonski said.
If the Fed’s decision-makers do this, “they should act deeply in their policies to avoid panic in financial markets.”
Other experts said an increase in the interest rate would calm financial markets as it would remove uncertainty about the moment the Fed will act.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared to be on track to increase the rate by 0.25% this month, the first small step towards slow tightening monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that he expected an interest rate rise this year despite the liberals’ high objections that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, growth in the labour market was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest percentage in more than seven years and close to the level considered by the Fed as total employment.
Salary gains have shown signs of growth.
And although inflation continued to fail to meet the central bank’s annual target, the Fed decision-makers claimed that a key reason was the temporary effect of the oil prices falling sharply.
The economy “may face higher rates and need them, given the labor market tensions,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began to fall into fibrillation at the end of this month, after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell by 16% below the record high in May, as investors feared that the slowdown of the Chinese economy would slow global growth.
The market rebounded somewhat this month, with the Dow index now at around 10% below the May high.
For the Fed decision-makers, market turmoil is added to the complex calculation of the moment of interest rate rise.
“Without what has happened in the financial markets and the news of the weakening of the Chinese economy in recent weeks, it would be firmer during the meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, an experienced researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and former Fed.
Now, he predicts that they will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy and they have almost no data to base on subsequent events in China," Oliner said.
The well-being of the global economy is not one of the major interests of the Fed, so it should practically not be taken into account in decision-making.
In reality, the Fed has become the world monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been enormous.
In 2013, President Ben S. Bernanke’s simple hint that the Fed could “stop” its monetary expansion triggered an earthquake in global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are more and more crowded, it is expected that Fed officials will not only monitor progress in other areas, but also consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
His decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy department at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, President of Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., said this month that “Fed has a history of oversized reaction to changes in the financial market that seem to have nothing to do with economic bases.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Commission, a decision-making body that supported the increase in interest rates, offered as an example the 1998-99 decisions.
A financial crisis that affected Asia prompted the Fed to reduce the reference rate by 0.75% in three meetings, “despite the implications with limited identification for U.S. development,” Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed officials returned to the declines.
The Fed should put the issue of financial stability first only in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market quake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England interest rate setting committee.
The recent turbulent period is not even far up to that level, he said.
“We certainly don’t want to get into the situation of fearing an increase in interest rates because the markets are upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act continues to hold the dual mandate and does not mention financial stability and, until something changes in this regard, I do not think it should take premature action.
