Weight Loss Surgery Could Be Useful in Diabetics With Mild Obesity
The benefits of weight loss surgery in people with mild obesity with type 2 diabetes may persist for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is still premature to say whether diabetics with mild obesity live longer after weight loss surgery than those who follow non-surgical treatments.
“It takes a long time to centralize data on mortality,” said Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, as she wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss surgeries, also called bariatric surgery, use various methods to reduce the stomach.
They reduce the sensation of hunger and limit the body’s ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted on people with mild obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
IMC, a unit of weight relative to height, is considered normal in the range of 18.5-24.9.
The IMC value of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with IMC over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your IMC by accessing: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Taiwan’s Min-Sheng General Hospital used the data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery – gastric bypass and gastric clottomy – in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The mean IMC in people who underwent surgical intervention decreased from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year in the study.
In the meantime, IMC in people who received non-surgical treatments against diabetes remained close to the same level, namely 29.
Of those who underwent surgery, diabetes was fully cured at 36% and partially at 28%.
In the group treated by medical methods, by comparison, diabetes was completely cured in only 1% and partially in only 2% of subjects.
In addition, blood pressure control, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors concluded.
The researchers also monitored blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood glucose over time.
Researchers write that the optimal level of hemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
After surgery, the mean level of hemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
However, in the group treated by medical methods, it remained at about 8%.
But this improved "glycemic control" - reflected by improved levels of hemoglobin A1c - did not reduce mortality by five years, according to chief researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared to the group with gastrectomy in the sleeve, the group with bypass surgery lost more weight (18.7 vs. 14.2 kg), recorded more significant decreases in CMI (7.4 vs. 5.1), and the group had a more likely A1c, a more likely 16%, and a more complete A1c (3.1% vs. 14.2 kg).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study conducted in high-weight people in Sweden that surgical intervention prolongs life, says Blackstone, of the University of Arizona, Faculty of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were about 29% less likely to die after 15 years, compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients undergoing surgery, Blackstone stated that it is an optimistic aspect for people with IMC under 35 interested in the procedure.
“This is the point where this work is critical because it claims that this surgery is safe in the lower IMC group,” without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking weight seriously when the patient's IMC reaches 27-30.
“I think we wait too long until we encourage people to take this issue seriously,” she said.
I think once they have accumulated these genetic changes that shortened their bodies predisposing them to obesity and diabetes, it’s extremely difficult to get back to normal.
